<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?><feed xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" xml:lang="en"><generator uri="https://jekyllrb.com/" version="4.3.4">Jekyll</generator><link href="https://sai-tv.github.io/feed.xml" rel="self" type="application/atom+xml"/><link href="https://sai-tv.github.io/" rel="alternate" type="text/html" hreflang="en"/><updated>2026-04-06T21:43:41+00:00</updated><id>https://sai-tv.github.io/feed.xml</id><title type="html">blank</title><subtitle>A simple, whitespace theme for academics. Based on [*folio](https://github.com/bogoli/-folio) design. </subtitle><entry><title type="html">Week 1: Inspecting GPT-2 Small with TransformerLens</title><link href="https://sai-tv.github.io/blog/2026/gpt2-attention-inspection/" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="Week 1: Inspecting GPT-2 Small with TransformerLens"/><published>2026-04-03T00:00:00+00:00</published><updated>2026-04-03T00:00:00+00:00</updated><id>https://sai-tv.github.io/blog/2026/gpt2-attention-inspection</id><content type="html" xml:base="https://sai-tv.github.io/blog/2026/gpt2-attention-inspection/"><![CDATA[<p>I really want to try understanding LLMs: interpretability seems the place to start.</p> <p>This one’s a first hands-on inspection of <strong>GPT-2 small</strong> (117 M parameters) using <a href="https://github.com/TransformerLensOrg/TransformerLens">TransformerLens</a>. This week, I wanted to:</p> <ol> <li>Load the model and verify tensor shapes at key hook points.</li> <li>Run three fixed prompts through <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">run_with_cache</code> and capture residual-stream activations.</li> <li>Save a compact activation summary to disk for later analysis and have a little interactive feature on this post where you can see activations of different layers and heads.</li> </ol> <p>The notebook below contains the full code, observations, and then a little interactive plot where you can play around with layers and heads. Patterns on first pass seem pretty all over the place; perhaps more analysis will clarify things.</p> <p>Two things sort of stood out: there’s an attention sink at the end-of-text token where a majority of the attention is directed in many of the heads and layers: normalizing without this portion gives somewhat of a more informative summary. Also, self-attention seems to also be a dominant phenomenon for tokens in many layers: there’s other ones that look at adjacent words and somewhat “understand” (?) their relationships? Curious. Is this how we learn too…</p> <p>The full code and observations are in the notebook below — click to expand.</p> <details> <summary style="cursor:pointer; font-weight:bold; padding:6px 0;">View notebook</summary> <div class="jupyter-notebook" style="position: relative; width: 100%; margin: 0 auto;"> <div class="jupyter-notebook-iframe-container"> <iframe src="/assets/jupyter/week1_inspection.ipynb.html" style="position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; border-style: none;" width="100%" height="100%" onload="this.parentElement.style.paddingBottom = (this.contentWindow.document.documentElement.scrollHeight + 10) + 'px'"></iframe> </div> </div> </details> <hr/> <h2 id="interactive-attention-explorer">Interactive attention explorer</h2> <p>Browse all 12 layers and 12 heads across three prompts, or view averages. Hover a cell for the exact weight.</p> <div id="attn-explorer" data-src="/assets/json/attention_data.json" style="max-width:540px; margin:2rem auto; font-family:monospace; font-size:0.9rem;"> <div style="display:flex; flex-wrap:wrap; gap:16px; margin-bottom:14px;"> <label style="display:flex; flex-direction:column; gap:4px;"> Prompt <select id="prompt-select" style="font-family:monospace; font-size:0.85rem; padding:3px 6px;"></select> </label> <label style="display:flex; flex-direction:column; gap:4px;"> View <select id="mode-select" style="font-family:monospace; font-size:0.85rem; padding:3px 6px;"> <option value="single">Single head</option> <option value="avg-heads">Avg across heads (fix layer)</option> <option value="avg-layers">Avg across layers (fix head)</option> </select> </label> <label style="display:flex; flex-direction:column; gap:4px; justify-content:flex-end;"> <span style="display:flex; align-items:center; gap:6px; cursor:pointer;"> <input type="checkbox" id="exclude-bos" style="cursor:pointer;"/> Exclude &lt;|endoftext|&gt; </span> </label> </div> <div style="display:flex; gap:32px; margin-bottom:14px;"> <label id="layer-label" style="display:flex; flex-direction:column; gap:4px; align-items:center;"> Layer <input type="range" id="layer-slider" min="0" max="11" value="0" style="width:160px;"/> <span id="layer-val">0</span> </label> <label id="head-label" style="display:flex; flex-direction:column; gap:4px; align-items:center;"> Head <input type="range" id="head-slider" min="0" max="11" value="0" style="width:160px;"/> <span id="head-val">0</span> </label> </div> <canvas id="attn-canvas"></canvas> <div id="attn-tooltip" style="position:absolute; display:none; pointer-events:none; background:rgba(0,0,0,0.85); color:#fff; padding:6px 8px; border-radius:4px; font-size:12px; line-height:1.2; z-index:10;"></div> <p id="attn-status" style="margin-top:10px; color:#666;"></p> </div> <script>!function(){function t(t,e){var n=document.getElementById("attn-status");n&&(n.textContent=t||"",n.style.color=e?"#b00020":"#666")}function e(){return+document.getElementById("layer-slider").value}function n(){return+document.getElementById("head-slider").value}function l(){return document.getElementById("mode-select").value}function a(){return document.getElementById("exclude-bos").checked}function r(t){return t.map(function(t){var e=t.map(function(t,e){return 0===e?0:t}),n=e.reduce(function(t,e){return t+e},0);return n>0?e.map(function(t){return t/n}):e})}function o(t){for(var e=t[0].length,n=[],l=0;l<e;l++){n[l]=[];for(var a=0;a<e;a++){for(var r=0,o=0;o<t.length;o++)r+=t[o][l][a];n[l][a]=r/t.length}}return n}function d(t,e,n,l){if("avg-head